\section*{Abstract}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{Abstract}
Skillens is a personalised recommendation system for educational content that reduces choice overload in online learning environments by producing ranked Top-$K$ recommendations. Many existing systems rely heavily on popularity or aggregate engagement signals without modelling learner context and item content. This project follows \textbf{Project Template 1 (CM3005 Data Science), Project Idea 1.1: Data-Driven Personalised Educational Content Recommendation} \citep{cm3005_template}.

The implemented system uses a \textbf{hybrid recommendation architecture} that combines \textbf{Collaborative Filtering (CF)} and \textbf{Content-Based Filtering (CBF)}. The CF component is implemented using an item-based neighbourhood approach (ItemKNN) derived from learner interaction histories, while the primary CBF component uses TF-IDF representations over item metadata. These signals are fused using weighted score combination to produce the final ranked list. In addition, a semantic embedding recommender based on Sentence-BERT is implemented as an alternative content-based model option within the artefact. The system also provides template-based explanations to accompany recommendations in a readable, user-facing format.

Offline evaluation is conducted on the Open University Learning Analytics Dataset (OULAD) \citep{kuzilek2017oulad} using a per-learner temporal split protocol and reports Precision@$K$, Recall@$K$, and nDCG@$K$ across baseline models (popularity, TF-IDF, ItemKNN) and the hybrid model. In the reported results, the hybrid model achieves \textbf{nDCG@10 = 0.573}, outperforming the popularity baseline (\textbf{0.384}) and the TF-IDF baseline (\textbf{0.440}), indicating that combining interaction-based and content-based signals improves ranked recommendation quality in this setting.

