\section{Introduction}

\subsection{Alignment with the CM3005 Data Science template}
This project is based on \textbf{Project Template 1 (CM3005 Data Science), Project Idea 1.1: Data-Driven Personalised Educational Content Recommendation} \citep{cm3005_template}. It follows the data science workflow of data understanding, data preparation, feature representation, modelling, evaluation, and refinement. This draft provides evidence of compliance by outlining the developed system, the experimental protocol, and quantitative performance analysis against baseline recommenders.

\subsection{Project motivation and context}
Online learning and MOOCs have proliferated, and educational material is widely available. However, the scale of content can make it difficult for learners to identify the most relevant and timely resources. Learners may navigate long and inefficient learning paths that do not reflect their background, pace, or learning goals.

Conventional recommendation techniques in learning environments are often based on popularity or aggregate engagement. While these techniques can be valuable for broad discovery, they can be context-independent and may not capture the meaning of items or a learner's needs. This motivates a personalised recommender that combines behaviour signals with content representations to generate more relevant ranked recommendations. In educational settings, explanations are also important because learners benefit from understanding why a resource was suggested before investing time in it.

\subsection{Problem statement and goals}

\subsubsection*{Problem statement}
This project addresses the following research question:
\begin{quote}
To what extent can a hybrid recommendation model, integrating learner interaction signals with text-based content representations, improve ranked recommendation accuracy compared with non-personalised baselines, while remaining reproducible and providing clear, user-facing explanations?
\end{quote}

\subsubsection*{Achieved objectives}

\subsubsection*{G1: Develop a hybrid recommendation model}
\begin{itemize}
  \item Implemented a hybrid approach that combines Collaborative Filtering (CF) and Content-Based Filtering (CBF).
  \item Implemented the primary CBF component using TF-IDF vectorisation over item metadata, and implemented an additional semantic embedding recommender (Sentence-BERT) as an alternative content-based model option in the artefact.
  \item Produced Top-$K$ ranked recommendations via weighted fusion of CF and CBF scores.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection*{G2: Conduct quantitative evaluation}
\begin{itemize}
  \item Evaluated system performance using a defined offline experimental protocol.
  \item Reported key metrics including Precision@$K$, Recall@$K$, and nDCG@$K$ and benchmarked against baseline models (popularity, TF-IDF, ItemKNN) and the hybrid model.
  \item Used per-learner temporal splitting to support generalisation and reduce overfitting risk in offline evaluation.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection*{G3: Implement an explainability component (XAI)}
\begin{itemize}
  \item Integrated template-based explanations so that recommendations are accompanied by short, readable rationales.
  \item Ensured explanation text is consistent with the signals used to generate recommendations and is suitable for presentation in a learner-facing interface.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Users and artefact overview}

\subsubsection*{Target users}
The primary users are online learners who need help selecting the next relevant educational resource. This includes:
\begin{itemize}
  \item Learners with limited interaction history, where personalisation is constrained by sparse signals.
  \item Continuing learners with interaction history who benefit from recommendations aligned with demonstrated interests.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection*{Artefact overview}
The artefact is a hybrid educational content recommender implemented as a Python system with a Streamlit web interface. The system:
\begin{itemize}
  \item Ingests learner interaction data and resource representations derived from OULAD.
  \item Generates ranked personalised recommendations using TF-IDF (content-based) and ItemKNN (collaborative filtering), and fuses these signals into a final Top-$K$ list.
  \item Includes a semantic embedding recommender (Sentence-BERT) as an additional content-based model option within the artefact.
  \item Provides template-based explanation outputs to justify why an item was recommended.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection*{Dataset and development strategy}
The framework uses the Open University Learning Analytics Dataset (OULAD) \citep{kuzilek2017oulad} as the primary dataset for training and evaluation. The dataset includes \textbf{10,655,280} VLE interaction records (studentVle) and \textbf{32,593} student-module-presentation records (studentInfo) spanning \textbf{22} module presentations, alongside demographic attributes such as gender, age band, highest education level, region, disability status, and socio-economic indicators. These characteristics support realistic recommender experimentation under sparse and heterogeneous learner behaviour. A Coursera course catalogue is used only to support interface demonstration when external URLs are required for clickable UI recommendations. All quantitative evaluation results and reported metrics in this draft are derived exclusively from OULAD-based interaction data.

As shown in the evaluation results, the hybrid model achieves \textbf{nDCG@10 = 0.573}, compared with \textbf{0.384} for the popularity baseline and \textbf{0.440} for TF-IDF. ItemKNN also performs strongly (\textbf{nDCG@10 = 0.538}), indicating that interaction-based neighbourhood structure contributes meaningfully in this dataset. Overall, the results show that combining interaction and content signals improves ranked recommendation quality over non-personalised baselines in the reported offline setting.
