\section{Literature Review}

\subsection{Overview and thematic scope}
Skillens is a data-driven recommender for educational content. The system targets learning settings where interaction data can be sparse, resources are often described through short text and metadata, and users benefit from recommendations that are both accurate and understandable. Educational recommendation differs from entertainment recommenders because errors are costly: irrelevant resources waste time, reduce learner momentum, and can misalign learners with prerequisite knowledge. Therefore, the literature reviewed here focuses on (i) sparsity and cold-start constraints in education, (ii) hybrid recommenders as a practical response, (iii) semantic representations for text-heavy catalogues, and (iv) trust and explainability considerations.

The chapter is organised around six themes that map directly to the project goals and the implemented architecture. First, it reviews limitations of single-method recommenders in educational contexts. Second, it motivates hybridisation as a practical design space for sparsity and cold start. Third, it reviews semantic representations (BERT-style embeddings) and explains when they improve content understanding beyond shallow bag-of-words methods. Fourth, it discusses learner context, learning trajectory, and temporal dynamics. Fifth, it focuses on trust and explainability in educational AI. Finally, it reviews offline evaluation pitfalls (leakage and split design) that strongly influence the credibility of recommender results. Each theme ends with an explicit implication for Skillens that links to the Design (Chapter 3), Implementation (Chapter 4), and Evaluation (Chapter 5) chapters.

\subsection{Limitations of single-method recommenders in educational settings}

\subsubsection{Sparsity, cold start, and pedagogical mismatch}
Learning platforms typically expose a large catalogue, while each learner interacts with only a small fraction of available resources. This results in a sparse user-item interaction matrix, which can make collaborative filtering unstable because similarity and co-occurrence patterns are weak for many users and items. Sparsity also amplifies cold-start issues: new learners have limited interaction history, and newly added courses or resources have insufficient engagement. In such settings, purely interaction-driven models tend to favour popular items, which reduces coverage and can disadvantage learners whose trajectories do not follow mainstream patterns.

Educational recommendation also faces pedagogical mismatch. A popular item among similar users may still be inappropriate if it assumes prerequisites, uses unfamiliar tools, or is pitched at an unsuitable level. Surveys of recommender systems show that purely collaborative approaches can suffer when they do not incorporate item content or context that is pedagogically meaningful \citep{sabiri2025}. In education, relevance is not only about similarity of consumption patterns but also about suitability for learning goals and learner readiness.

\textit{Implication for Skillens:} collaborative signals are valuable but insufficient alone. Skillens therefore implements an interaction-based component (ItemKNN) while also incorporating a content-based component, enabling relevance to be supported by both behaviour and item text characteristics (Chapter 4).

\subsubsection{Limits of shallow text matching}
Content-based filtering (CBF) is commonly implemented using bag-of-words representations such as TF-IDF over titles and descriptions. This approach is simple, transparent, and often a strong baseline. However, shallow representations can struggle with synonymy (different words expressing the same topic) and polysemy (the same token having different meanings depending on context). In educational catalogues, descriptions are often short and inconsistent across providers, which further reduces the reliability of strict token overlap. Prior work notes that purely lexical similarity can miss semantic relationships that matter for relevance \citep{sabiri2025}.

Despite these limitations, TF-IDF remains important for reproducibility and interpretability. It provides a defensible baseline and allows systematic comparison when more complex semantic models are introduced.

\textit{Implication for Skillens:} Skillens uses TF-IDF as a primary content-based baseline and incorporates a semantic embedding recommender as an additional content model option in the artefact (Chapter 4). Evaluation in this draft report focuses on models that are fully integrated into the scoring and evaluation pipeline.

\subsection{Hybrid recommenders as a practical response}

Hybrid recommenders combine collaborative and content-based signals to mitigate the weaknesses of using either method alone. The general rationale is that collaborative components exploit behavioural structure when history exists, while content-based components generalise to new or rarely interacted items using item descriptions. Prior work demonstrates that hybridisation can improve recommendation quality, particularly when interaction data are sparse and item text is informative \citep{remadnia2025}. In educational contexts, this can be especially valuable because learners may have limited history for many modules, while resources still carry textual cues (module titles, learning outcomes, platform activity context).

Hybridisation is not a single method but a design space. Survey work describes switching strategies for cold start, feature augmentation approaches that inject content features into collaborative models, and weighted blending strategies that combine independent model outputs \citep{sabiri2025}. These choices matter because hybrid systems can perform well on aggregate metrics while still failing cold-start users if the hybrid method does not adapt to how much history is available. For example, a cold-start learner might require a content-first mode, while learners with longer histories benefit from interaction-driven structure.

\textit{Implication for Skillens:} Skillens adopts weighted blending for the hybrid ranker, combining an interaction-based model (ItemKNN) with a content-based model (TF-IDF). The fusion weight is treated as a tunable parameter and is analysed through ablation-style evaluation (Chapters 4 and 5). Cold-start adaptation is treated as a key design requirement, and its evaluation is addressed carefully when the split protocol yields defensible cold-start slices (Chapter 5).

\subsection{Semantic representations with BERT-style embeddings}

\subsubsection{Why contextual embeddings can improve content understanding}
A growing body of recommender research uses contextual embeddings instead of bag-of-words text features. Transformer-based encoders (for example, BERT variants) produce dense vectors that can capture semantic similarity even when two descriptions share few exact tokens. In settings where learners specify goals in natural language and course descriptions vary widely, embeddings can better represent meaning than strict token overlap. For example, recent work exploring BERT-based recommendation pipelines reports improvements over TF-IDF for semantic retrieval and ranking metrics in text-driven recommendation contexts \citep{sangeetha2025}.

Figure~\ref{fig:tfidf_bert_hybrid} provides a conceptual illustration of why embeddings can help: TF-IDF clusters are sensitive to surface vocabulary, while contextual embeddings can group semantically related content more robustly.

\begin{figure}[!htbp]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.90\textwidth]{1.png}
  \caption{Conceptual illustration of how TF-IDF and BERT-style embeddings can differ in semantic coherence and cluster separation (informed by \citet{sangeetha2025}).}
  \label{fig:tfidf_bert_hybrid}
\end{figure}

\textit{Implication for Skillens:} Skillens implements a semantic embedding recommender (Sentence-BERT) as a content-based model option in the artefact (Chapter~4). In this draft report, TF-IDF remains the primary content model in the evaluated hybrid fusion pipeline for clarity, reproducibility, and controlled comparison.

\subsubsection{Integrating behavioural signals with text signals}
Beyond retrieval, behavioural signals and text signals can be integrated in several ways: by blending independent scores, by using text embeddings as features inside a collaborative model, or by learning a joint model that consumes both representations. Work on combining behavioural and content signals emphasises that text can carry preference information not fully captured by clicks or ratings \citep{wu2024}. Even when Skillens does not model reviews or rich narratives, educational resources include text and metadata that can provide a useful relevance prior, particularly in early user history.

\textit{Implication for Skillens:} Skillens treats textual representations as first-class signals in the recommender and fuses them with interaction-based similarity through a controlled weighted hybrid design (Chapter 4). This is evaluated against standalone baselines to quantify gains (Chapter 5).

\subsubsection{Cold start and metadata-driven recommendation in education}
Education-focused course recommenders frequently rely on metadata and descriptions to provide immediate value for new users. Hybrid approaches that incorporate embeddings and structured features can support useful recommendations even when collaborative history is limited \citep{hasoon2025}. This supports a cold-start design pattern: content-first recommendations initially, with collaborative signals becoming more influential as interaction history grows.

\textit{Implication for Skillens:} Skillens includes strong content-based baselines (TF-IDF and a semantic embedding option) so the system can function with limited history. Cold-start remains a central requirement and is evaluated only under split conditions that produce defensible cold-start slices (Chapter 5).

\subsection{Integrating context and learning trajectory}

A key distinction between education and many consumer recommendation settings is that relevance depends on learner state. A resource can be topically related yet inappropriate if it is too advanced or too basic. Context-aware recommendation approaches combine text representations with structured context (for example, education level, background signals, or recent learning behaviour). Prior work combining embeddings with contextual variables demonstrates that structured context can remove contextually wrong recommendations and improve ranking quality \citep{mpia2023}. Although Skillens focuses on offline ranking using interaction traces and item metadata, this literature motivates careful treatment of learner context as a design consideration.

Figure~\ref{fig:context_fusion} provides a conceptual view of context fusion, showing how learner context features can complement text representations.

\begin{figure}[!htbp]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.90\textwidth]{2.png}
  \caption{Conceptual view of context fusion: combining structured learner features with text-based representations to form a context-aware user representation (based on \citet{mpia2023}).}
  \label{fig:context_fusion}
\end{figure}

Learner needs also change over time. Temporal dynamics research highlights that models capturing evolving preferences can outperform static approaches \citep{wu2024}. In educational environments, a learner's recent activity may be more predictive of next-step relevance than older interactions. Even without complex sequential neural models, temporal evaluation design and recency-aware profiling can improve realism and reduce optimistic bias.

\textit{Implication for Skillens:} Skillens adopts a per-learner temporal split protocol in offline evaluation to better reflect future recommendation conditions (Chapter 5). Recency effects and richer context integration are treated as extensions that can be incorporated through feature design and/or reweighting strategies once baseline integrity is established.

\subsection{Trust and explainability in educational AI}

\subsubsection{Explainability as a requirement in education}
In education, recommendations influence what learners study next and can shape learning outcomes. Transparency helps learners assess relevance before committing time, and it supports user trust. Work in educational AI indicates that interpretability can help stakeholders understand model behaviour and improve adoption \citep{hoq2023}. While Skillens focuses on recommendation rather than prediction, the same motivation applies: explanations should be understandable to learners and should reflect the signals used to generate the recommendation.

\textit{Implication for Skillens:} Skillens includes a user-facing explanation layer in the Streamlit artefact, providing short template-based rationales that remain readable and consistent with the available model signals (Chapter 4).

\subsubsection{SHAP-based explainability and natural language justifications}
Recent work proposes explainability pipelines that compute feature attributions (for example, SHAP) and then render human-readable natural language justifications \citep{rahim2025}. This is attractive because it aims to maintain fidelity to model evidence while presenting explanations in accessible language. In recommender settings, this often means attributing recommendation scores to salient features and expressing them in constrained natural language.

Figure~\ref{fig:explainability_pipeline} summarises this conceptual pipeline.

\begin{figure}[!htbp]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.90\textwidth]{3.png}
  \caption{Conceptual workflow for explanation generation in recommenders: compute feature attributions (for example, SHAP), select salient factors, then render a constrained natural language explanation (informed by \citet{rahim2025}).}
  \label{fig:explainability_pipeline}
\end{figure}

\textit{Implication for Skillens:} this draft report uses template-based explanations as a defensible baseline for readability and consistency. Attribution-based explanations (for example, SHAP grounded explanations) remain an extension pathway once a feature-based scoring model is integrated end-to-end and evaluated under stable protocols.

\subsubsection{Limitations and guardrails for post-hoc explanations}
Explainability can be misleading if users interpret post-hoc explanations as causal, or if explanations reflect spurious correlations. Educational datasets can contain proxies (for example, region or activity patterns) that correlate with outcomes without being meaningful learning factors. Critiques of post-hoc explanation methods note that explanation quality depends not only on readability but also on robustness and appropriate interpretation \citep{hooshyar2024}. Therefore, educational recommenders should restrict learner-facing explanations to pedagogically meaningful factors and avoid presenting fragile correlations as definitive reasons.

\textit{Implication for Skillens:} Skillens keeps explanations bounded and readable in the draft artefact, and treats explanation stability as a requirement to be evaluated when more detailed feature-based explanations are introduced in later iterations.

\subsection{Offline evaluation pitfalls: leakage, bias, and split design}

\subsubsection{Why offline evaluation can be misleading}
Recommender evaluation is sensitive to protocol choices. Many offline studies report optimistic metrics because of leakage, weak baselines, or unrealistic splits. Leakage can occur when information from the test period influences representations learned from the training data, or when candidate sets are constructed in a way that implicitly exposes test items. In education datasets, leakage is especially likely if interactions are aggregated across time without respecting chronology, because learners' later activity can leak future preferences into the training profile.

A second pitfall is popularity bias. Simple popularity baselines can appear strong in offline metrics when test items overlap heavily with globally popular content. If evaluation protocols do not control for popularity effects and novelty, results can overstate personalisation gains. In addition, sparsity means that many users may have too few held-out interactions to evaluate fairly, which can skew metrics toward heavy users.

\textit{Implication for Skillens:} Skillens uses a per-learner temporal splitting protocol and evaluates multiple baselines (popularity, TF-IDF, ItemKNN) alongside the hybrid model. This supports credible comparison and reduces optimistic bias (Chapter 5). Protocol limitations and coverage constraints are explicitly discussed as part of the evaluation analysis.

\subsubsection{Temporal splits and user-level integrity}
Temporal evaluation protocols help ensure that models are evaluated on future interactions rather than randomly mixed histories. They also align with real deployment, where the system recommends the next resource based on past behaviour. However, temporal splits require careful handling to ensure that evaluation uses genuinely held-out behaviour and that users have sufficient interactions for meaningful testing.

\textit{Implication for Skillens:} temporal splitting is adopted as a core evaluation design choice, and split integrity is validated programmatically before producing final metrics and plots (Chapter 5).

\subsection{Summary: from literature to architecture}
Across the reviewed work, three requirements emerge.

First, hybridisation is justified as a practical response to sparsity because content and interaction signals complement each other, and the hybrid design should be evaluated against strong baselines \citep{remadnia2025,sabiri2025}. Second, semantic understanding matters in text-heavy educational catalogues, motivating the inclusion of semantic embeddings as an artefact option alongside transparent lexical baselines \citep{sangeetha2025,wu2024,hasoon2025}. Third, educational recommenders require trust and careful interpretation, so explanations should remain readable and aligned with model evidence, and post-hoc explanation limitations should be treated explicitly \citep{rahim2025,hoq2023,hooshyar2024}.

These requirements motivate the architecture in the next chapter: an interaction-driven collaborative component, a text-driven content component, a weighted hybrid fusion stage, and a learner-facing explanation layer. Chapter 3 details the resulting design, Chapter 4 describes the implementation choices, and Chapter 5 evaluates the implemented models under the chosen offline protocol while documenting the protocol assumptions and limitations.

