\subsection{System overview and end-to-end workflow}
\label{sec:system_overview}

Skillens follows a modular architecture so that (1) baselines can be evaluated independently, (2) hybrid fusion can be tested via ablations, and (3) leakage checks and evaluation scripts remain separate from the interactive demo.

\begin{figure}[!t]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.95\textwidth]{12.png}
  \caption{Skillens end-to-end workflow: learner goal input, content representation, candidate retrieval, optional collaborative scoring, hybrid fusion, Top-$N$ output, deterministic explanations, and feedback logging.}
  \label{fig:end_to_end_workflow}
\end{figure}

The workflow is designed to behave sensibly under cold start: when the user has no interaction history, Skillens uses content similarity only. When interaction history exists (in offline evaluation or future deployment), Skillens can compute an item-based collaborative score and blend it with content similarity.

\subsection{Data sources and pipeline}
\label{sec:data_pipeline}

Skillens uses a \textbf{dual-dataset packaging strategy} to avoid a common evaluation pitfall: mixing a UI demo catalogue with evaluation claims.

\paragraph{Primary dataset (evaluation): OULAD.}
OULAD provides anonymised learners, module presentations, and interaction traces (VLE activity events), enabling realistic offline testing with time-aware splits \citep{kuzilek2017oulad}. In the submitted implementation, OULAD is the \textbf{only} source used for quantitative evaluation claims.

\paragraph{Secondary dataset (UI demonstration only): Coursera course catalogue.}
A separate course catalogue is included solely to make the UI feel realistic (titles and links). It is not used to justify offline performance claims.

\subsubsection{Item definition used in the implementation}
A key design decision is the \textbf{item granularity}. In the submitted build, Skillens treats each OULAD \textbf{module presentation} as a recommendable item (e.g., \texttt{oulad\_AAA\_2013J}), rather than recommending individual VLE resources. This decision is intentional:

\begin{itemize}
  \item It matches the strongest ``course selection'' framing in Template 1.1.
  \item It keeps the evaluation unit consistent across content features and interactions.
  \item It reduces the risk of overclaiming fine-grained pedagogy when the available text is limited.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Preprocessing and artefacts produced}
The pipeline is implemented as scripted steps that produce intermediate CSV artefacts under \texttt{data/processed/}. The core steps are:

\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Ingestion and normalisation:} OULAD tables are loaded and normalised into consistent identifiers for learners and module presentations.
  \item \textbf{Interaction construction:} learner VLE activity is mapped to module presentations to form implicit feedback events. Each event represents engagement (click activity) associated with a module presentation.
  \item \textbf{Content text construction:} each item receives a text representation (title plus structured tokens such as provider/source), enabling TF-IDF vectorisation and optional semantic embedding.
  \item \textbf{Temporal splitting (evaluation constraint):} train/validation/test splits are created per learner using time order so that training interactions precede validation and test interactions for that learner.
\end{itemize}

This is a design constraint, not a cosmetic choice: the entire evaluation protocol depends on time-respecting splitting to avoid leakage.

\subsection{Recommender architecture}
\label{sec:recommender_architecture}

Skillens implements multiple recommenders to support ablation-based evaluation and to demonstrate technical depth beyond a single-method prototype. The system includes:

\begin{enumerate}
  \item \textbf{Popularity baseline} for calibration.
  \item \textbf{TF-IDF content-based recommender} as a strong, reproducible cold-start baseline.
  \item \textbf{Semantic embedding recommender} (Sentence-BERT) as an optional content model in the UI.
  \item \textbf{ItemKNN collaborative filtering} using implicit feedback events.
  \item \textbf{Hybrid recommender} combining TF-IDF and ItemKNN via score-level fusion with a cold-start fallback.
\end{enumerate}

\subsubsection{Content-based ranking with TF-IDF}
Each item is represented by a text field. The TF-IDF model maps item texts into sparse vectors and computes cosine similarity between a learner query and each item:

\begin{equation}
\text{sim}(\mathbf{q}, \mathbf{i}) = \frac{\mathbf{q} \cdot \mathbf{i}}{\|\mathbf{q}\| \, \|\mathbf{i}\|}
\end{equation}

In the UI, $\mathbf{q}$ is derived from the learner's free-text goal. In offline evaluation, a realistic proxy query is built from the learner's training-history item titles only, so the test set is not used to construct the query.

\subsubsection{Semantic embeddings (optional model in the UI)}
Skillens also contains a semantic content model based on Sentence-BERT (\texttt{all-MiniLM-L6-v2}). This model is integrated as a selectable recommender in the Streamlit UI to support semantic matching beyond token overlap. In the submitted evaluation results (Chapter~5), the primary reported content model is TF-IDF for reproducibility and speed. The semantic model remains available for demonstration and as a clear extension path for the final submission.

\subsubsection{Collaborative filtering with ItemKNN}
To incorporate behavioural similarity when interaction history exists, Skillens implements item-based collaborative filtering. ItemKNN computes item-to-item similarity from implicit feedback events and scores candidates based on similarity to items the learner interacted with previously. ItemKNN is used because it is:

\begin{itemize}
  \item appropriate for implicit feedback settings,
  \item interpretable compared to deep CF variants,
  \item suitable for a modular hybrid pipeline.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Hybrid fusion and cold-start fallback}
Skillens combines content and collaborative scores at the score level:

\begin{equation}
\text{score}_{hybrid}(u,i) = w_{c}\,\text{score}_{content}(u,i) + w_{k}\,\text{score}_{knn}(u,i)
\end{equation}

where $w_{c}$ and $w_{k}$ are fixed weights used consistently throughout the evaluation runs. Importantly, the hybrid implementation includes a \textbf{cold-start safeguard}: if the learner has no usable history for collaborative scoring, the recommender falls back to the content model rather than producing low-quality or empty outputs.

This design supports clean ablations in evaluation:
\begin{itemize}
  \item Popularity only
  \item TF-IDF only
  \item ItemKNN only
  \item Hybrid (TF-IDF + ItemKNN)
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Explanation subsystem (bounded, deterministic XAI)}
\label{sec:xai_design}

The marker feedback from the preliminary submission emphasised that explainability should not remain purely ``planned''. In the submitted build, Skillens implements a deterministic explanation layer that is intentionally bounded:

\begin{itemize}
  \item it explains \textbf{model behaviour} (why an item ranked highly),
  \item it avoids causal educational claims (e.g., ``this will improve your grades''),
  \item it is reproducible (the same inputs produce the same explanation).
\end{itemize}

The current explanation engine renders short templates using available evidence signals (the recommendation score and item popularity context). This provides transparency that is aligned with what the implemented models can justify. More advanced explainers (for example, SHAP over learned feature models) are included in the repository as extension modules, but are not claimed as the primary explanation method unless explicitly used in the evaluation outputs.

\subsection{User interface and artefact packaging}
\label{sec:ui_packaging}

Skillens includes a Streamlit interface so that a marker can interact with the system without running evaluation scripts. The UI supports:

\begin{itemize}
  \item entering a free-text goal statement,
  \item selecting a recommender variant (TF-IDF, Semantic, Hybrid),
  \item selecting Top-$N$,
  \item viewing recommendations with short explanations,
  \item submitting explicit feedback (relevant / not relevant).
\end{itemize}

Feedback is logged to a CSV file under \texttt{data/feedback/} to keep evaluation runs separate from interactive usage.

\subsection{Evaluation design (draft report scope)}
\label{sec:evaluation_design}

The preliminary feedback highlighted that evaluation must progress from qualitative discussion to executed quantitative results. Skillens therefore adopts a strict offline evaluation protocol that:

\begin{itemize}
  \item uses \textbf{per-learner temporal splitting} so training precedes testing for each learner,
  \item evaluates Top-$K$ ranking quality using standard recommender metrics,
  \item compares against explicit baselines and ablations.
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{Primary ranking metrics.}
The core reported metrics are:
\begin{itemize}
  \item Precision@$K$
  \item Recall@$K$
  \item NDCG@$K$
\end{itemize}

These metrics match the recommendation task (Top-$K$ ranking under implicit feedback) and avoid inappropriate ``accuracy'' framing.

\paragraph{Cold start definition used in this build.}
Skillens is designed to handle cold start through content-first recommendation in the UI. For offline evaluation, the temporal split primarily evaluates \textbf{next-item prediction under history} (because all users appear in training by design). A stricter ``new-user'' cold-start protocol is treated as an extension for the final submission (for example, holding out a subset of users entirely from training).

\subsection{Risk register (evaluation credibility)}
\label{sec:risk_register}

The design explicitly prioritises evaluation credibility because inflated results are heavily penalised.

\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Leakage risk:} mitigated by per-user temporal splitting and by constructing evaluation queries from training history only.
  \item \textbf{Sparse-history instability:} mitigated by the hybrid fallback to content-only when collaborative evidence is insufficient.
  \item \textbf{Explanation overclaim:} mitigated by bounded, deterministic templates and by avoiding causal claims.
  \item \textbf{Demo vs evaluation contamination:} mitigated by separating the UI catalogue dataset from OULAD-based evaluation claims.
\end{itemize}


