\section{Implementation}

This chapter presents the implementation of Skillens, and in particular, the code, architecture, and system design. The work is based on the design principles presented in Chapter 3. Further, we tackle the technical challenges that came with creating a hybrid recommender system on actual OULAD data.

\subsection{System architecture and code organization}

The system is implemented as a modular Python application with the following structure:

\begin{verbatim}
src/
|-- data/          % OULAD ingestion and processing
|-- models/       % Recommender models
|-- eval/         % Evaluation framework
|-- explain/      % Explanation generation
`-- app/          % Streamlit UI
\end{verbatim}

Each module is designed for independent validation and supports controlled ablation studies. The architecture separates data processing, model training, evaluation, and user interface concerns.

\subsection{OULAD data pipeline}

The OULAD data pipeline processes 10.6 million interaction events into a format suitable for recommendation. The implementation handles the scale of OULAD through chunked processing and efficient data structures.

\subsubsection{Data ingestion}

OULAD data is ingested from CSV files in the \texttt{anonymisedData} directory. The pipeline loads three key tables:
\begin{itemize}
  \item \texttt{studentVle.csv}: VLE click events (10,655,280 records)
  \item \texttt{vle.csv}: VLE resource metadata
  \item \texttt{studentInfo.csv}: Learner demographics
\end{itemize}

The ingestion process maps individual VLE activities to module-level items. This aggregation creates more meaningful recommendations than individual VLE resources, as modules represent complete learning units.

\subsubsection{Interaction construction}

Interactions are built from VLE click events. The implementation processes data in chunks of 200,000 records to handle memory constraints:

\begin{verbatim}
for chunk in pd.read_csv(student_vle_path, chunksize=200_000):
    chunk["item_id"] = chunk["id_site"].map(site_to_item)
    chunk["timestamp"] = base_date + pd.to_timedelta(chunk["date"])
    % Aggregate and save
\end{verbatim}

\normalfont
Each interaction record contains \texttt{user\_id}, \texttt{item\_id}, \texttt{timestamp}, and \texttt{event\_type}. The interaction strength is computed as log-transformed click counts to reduce the influence of highly active users.


\subsubsection{Temporal splitting}
Additionally, it uses per-user temporal splits to prevent data leakage. In this regard, the interactions for each user are sorted based on time stamps and then split into train, validation, and test with (60\%), (20\%), and (20\%), respectively. This is done to guarantee that training interactions occur before testing interactions.

