\subsection{Recommender model implementations}

Three recommender models are implemented: popularity baseline, TF-IDF content-based, ItemKNN collaborative filtering, and a hybrid that combines them.

\subsubsection{Popularity baseline}

The popularity recommender ranks items by global interaction frequency. This serves as a simple baseline to measure improvement from personalized approaches. Implementation is straightforward: count interactions per item, sort by count, return top-$K$.

\subsubsection{TF-IDF content-based recommender}

The TF-IDF recommender uses scikit-learn's \texttt{TfidfVectorizer} with a maximum of 5,000 features and English stop words. Each item is represented as a combined text field from title, description, and tags.

The recommendation process:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Vectorize all items during training (fit phase)
  \item Vectorize the user goal at request time
  \item Compute cosine similarity between goal vector and all item vectors
  \item Return top-$K$ items by similarity score
\end{enumerate}

This provides strong cold-start coverage since it requires no user interaction history.

\subsubsection{ItemKNN collaborative filtering}

ItemKNN implements item-based collaborative filtering. The model computes item-item similarity using cosine similarity on the user-item interaction matrix. For each user, recommendations are generated by finding items similar to those the user has interacted with.

The similarity computation:
\begin{equation}
\text{sim}(i, j) = \frac{\sum_{u} r_{u,i} \cdot r_{u,j}}{\sqrt{\sum_{u} r_{u,i}^2} \cdot \sqrt{\sum_{u} r_{u,j}^2}}
\end{equation}

where $r_{u,i}$ is user $u$'s interaction with item $i$. The model uses $k=50$ nearest neighbors by default.

\subsubsection{Hybrid recommender}

The hybrid recommender combines TF-IDF and ItemKNN using weighted score fusion. The implementation normalizes both content and collaborative scores to [0, 1] range before fusion to ensure fair combination:

\begin{verbatim}
hybrid_score = w_content * content_score + w_cf * cf_score
\end{verbatim}

Default weights are $w_{content} = 0.6$ and $w_{cf} = 0.4$, optimized on the validation set. For cold-start users with no interaction history, the system uses only content-based recommendations.

\subsection{Evaluation leakage fix}

A critical bug was identified and fixed in the evaluation pipeline. The original implementation built user goal queries from test set items, causing data leakage. The fix ensures queries are built exclusively from training data:

\begin{verbatim}
% FIXED: Build query from TRAIN history only
user_train = train_df[train_df["user_id"] == user_id]
train_items = user_train["item_id"].tolist()
goal_text = " ".join(item_lookup.loc[item_id, "title"] 
                     for item_id in train_items[:3])
\end{verbatim}

After fixing the evaluation leakage by evaluating only on novel test items (items not in user's training history), results became realistic for educational RecSys with high sparsity. TF-IDF achieves NDCG@10 of 0.44, Hybrid achieves 0.57, and ItemKNN achieves 0.54, all significantly better than the Popularity baseline of 0.38.

\subsection{Explanation subsystem}

The explanation system giving explanations for each recommendation. The implementation identifies main factors for matching (content similarity, collaborative filters), which are then presented in deterministic template form.

Explanations for content-based recommendations involve an indicator of keyword matches between the user goal and item contents, while for hybrid recommendations, they involve an indicator of whether the recommendation is based on content, collaborative filtering, or both.

\subsection{User interface}

The system includes a Streamlit web interface for demonstration and testing. The interface supports:
