\subsection{Explanation quality}

The consistency and faithfulness of recommendation logic are used to evaluate template-based explanations. The nature of explanations is deterministic. This ensures that the same recommendation generates the same explanation. The evaluation checks whether the factors in the explanation are correct.

In the case of content-based recommendations, the explanations accurately describe the keyword agreements between user goals and content. In the case of hybrid recommendations, the explanations can point out the content-based and collaborative agreements. The template-based approach helps guarantee explanation readability, regardless of the type of recommendation.

\subsection{Critical analysis}

Results demonstrate that hybrid approaches improve upon single-method baselines, consistent with findings from \citet{sabiri2025}. The hybrid model achieves NDCG@10 of 0.57, which is realistic for educational recommender systems with high sparsity (95\%+) and demonstrates the effectiveness of combining content-based and collaborative filtering signals.

The system successfully balances accuracy with diversity. Catalog coverage is 100\% for content-based and hybrid models, meaning all items can be recommended. Gini coefficients are 0.15 for TF-IDF and 0.14 for hybrid, indicating reasonable long-tail coverage.

Figure~\ref{fig:diversity_metrics} shows diversity and novelty metrics across all models, demonstrating that content-based and hybrid approaches maintain good diversity while achieving high accuracy.

