\section{Conclusion}

This chapter summarizes the achievements of Skillens, discusses contributions to educational recommender systems, acknowledges limitations, and suggests directions for future work.

\subsection{Summary of achievements}

Skillens is successful in deploying a hybrid recommendation system for educational content, using real data from the OULAD dataset. The system reports an NDCG@10 value of 0.57 for the hybrid solution, indicating a 49 percent increase above popularity baselines (NDCG@10 = 0.38). The content-based TF-IDF model achieves NDCG@10 of 0.44, demonstrating semantic matching capability, while the ItemKNN collaborative filtering model achieves NDCG@10 of 0.54, showing strong performance despite extreme sparsity.

The implementation comprises an end-to-end data pipeline for 10.6M OULAD interactions, inclusion of different recommender system strategies (Popularity, TF-IDF, ItemKNN, Hybrid), as well as providing template-based explanations. In addition, the evaluation metrics comprise temporal splitting with leakage prevention, applying non-parametric statistical significance examination, and incorporating fairness evaluation of demographic groups.

Key technical achievements include:
\begin{itemize}
  \item Successful integration of OULAD data with proper temporal splitting
  \item Implementation of hybrid recommendation combining content-based and collaborative filtering
  \item Fix of critical evaluation leakage bug that invalidated initial results
  \item Comprehensive evaluation with bootstrap confidence intervals and statistical significance testing
  \item Fairness analysis framework across multiple demographic dimensions
\end{itemize}

The system demonstrates that content-based filtering is essential for educational recommendation, especially under extreme sparsity conditions. The hybrid approach successfully adapts from content-only recommendations for cold-start users to collaborative-enhanced recommendations for active users.

\subsection{Contributions to educational recommender systems}

This work contributes to educational recommender systems in several ways:

\textbf{Comprehensive fairness evaluation.} To our knowledge, this is the first work to systematically evaluate recommendation fairness across multiple demographic dimensions (gender, age, education, region, disability, socioeconomic background) on real educational interaction data from OULAD. The analysis reveals performance gaps that motivate future mitigation strategies.

\textbf{Evaluation methodology.} The work demonstrates a rigorous evaluation protocol using per-user temporal splits with explicit leakage prevention. The documentation of the evaluation leakage bug and its fix provides a valuable lesson for future recommender system evaluations.

\textbf{Hybrid system under extreme sparsity.} The work demonstrates that hybrid recommenders can be effective even under extreme sparsity (95\%+), where collaborative filtering alone fails. The content-based component provides stable performance while collaborative signals contribute when sufficient interaction history exists.

\textbf{Transparent trade-offs.} Unlike prior work optimizing solely for engagement metrics, this work demonstrates explicit trade-offs between accuracy, diversity, and fairness. The system achieves 100\% catalog coverage while maintaining reasonable accuracy, providing actionable insights for educational platform designers.

\subsection{Limitations}

Several limitations should be acknowledged:

\textbf{Data sparsity constraints.} OULAD's extreme sparsity (95\%+) limits absolute performance compared to commercial systems. However, ItemKNN achieves NDCG@10 of 0.54, demonstrating that collaborative filtering can be effective even under extreme sparsity when combined with proper evaluation methodology. The hybrid system benefits from both content-based and collaborative filtering signals.

\textbf{Demographic gaps.} Fairness analysis reveals performance gaps across demographic groups. Older learners (55+) experience 27\% lower NDCG than younger learners. Learners with lower prior education see 24\% reduced performance. These gaps persist despite mitigation efforts and likely reflect both data sparsity in underrepresented groups and algorithmic bias toward majority patterns.

\textbf{Offline evaluation limitations.} The evaluation is entirely offline and cannot measure actual learning impact or user satisfaction. Offline metrics (Precision@K, Recall@K, NDCG@K) measure recommendation accuracy but not whether recommendations improve learning outcomes or user engagement.

\textbf{Domain specificity.} Results are specific to UK Open University distance learning context. The system's performance may not generalize to other educational settings such as MOOCs, in-person courses, or different subject domains.

\textbf{Explanation simplicity.} Template-based explanations are deterministic and readable but may oversimplify the recommendation process. The explanations do not capture complex interactions between content and collaborative signals.

\subsection{Future work}

Several directions for future work would strengthen the system:

\textbf{Longitudinal user studies.} Conduct real-world user studies to measure learning outcomes and user satisfaction. This would validate whether offline accuracy metrics correlate with actual educational value.

\textbf{Expert-validated skill ontologies.} Integrate expert-annotated skill ontologies to improve content representation and enable prerequisite-aware recommendations. This would address pedagogical mismatch more systematically.

\textbf{Advanced fairness mitigation.} Implement demographic parity constraints or fairness-aware training to reduce performance gaps across demographic groups. Explore techniques such as adversarial debiasing or demographic-aware reweighting.

\textbf{Sequential recommendation.} Extend the system to model learning trajectories and sequential dependencies. This would enable recommendations that consider prerequisite knowledge and learning progression.

\textbf{Cross-platform validation.} Evaluate the system on additional educational datasets (MOOCs, in-person courses) to assess generalizability. This would help identify which components are domain-specific versus domain-agnostic.

